{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YUNwfSuZLUZGSDLWV57NqZ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Installation\n     2→\n     3→This document covers the various ways to install Cloche on your machine.\n     4→\n     5→## Prerequisites\n     6→\n     7→All installation methods require:\n     8→\n     9→- **Docker** — Cloche runs workflows in containers\n    10→- **Git** — result extraction uses git worktrees\n    11→- **`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`** — for agent steps using Claude Code\n    12→\n    13→## Method Comparison\n    14→\n    15→| Method | Requires Go | Auto Docker Image | Best For |\n    16→|--------|:-----------:|:-----------------:|----------|\n    17→| [Build from source](#build-from-source) | Yes | Yes | Contributors, full control |\n    18→| [`go install`](#go-install) | Yes | No | Go developers, quick setup |\n    19→| [Pre-built binaries](#pre-built-release-binaries-planned) | No | No | Most users (planned) |\n    20→| [Homebrew](#homebrew-macos--linux-planned) | No | No | macOS / Linux (planned) |\n    21→| [Copy binaries](#copy-binaries) | No | No | Air-gapped or ad-hoc deploys |\n    22→| [Docker-only](#docker-only-usage-planned) | No | N/A | CI, no host install (planned) |\n    23→\n    24→All methods except Docker-only require building the `cloche-agent` Docker image\n    25→separately (unless the method does it automatically).\n    26→\n    27→## Build from Source\n    28→\n    29→Clone the repository, build the binaries and Docker image, and install them:\n    30→\n    31→```\n    32→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    33→cd cloche\n    34→make install\n    35→```\n    36→\n    37→`make install` builds all three binaries (`cloche`, `cloched`, `cloche-agent`),\n    38→builds the `cloche-agent:latest` Docker image, installs the binaries to\n    39→`~/.local/bin/`, and starts the daemon. You can change the install prefix:\n    40→\n    41→```\n    42→make install PREFIX=/usr/local\n    43→```\n    44→\n    45→Make sure the install prefix is on your `PATH`:\n    46→\n    47→```\n    48→export PATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\"\n    49→```\n    50→\n    51→### Build Requirements\n    52→\n    53→- Go 1.25+\n    54→\n    55→## `go install`\n    56→\n    57→If you have Go installed, you can install the binaries directly:\n    58→\n    59→```\n    60→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche@latest\n    61→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloched@latest\n    62→go install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche-agent@latest\n    63→```\n    64→\n    65→This places the binaries in `$GOPATH/bin` (or `$HOME/go/bin` by default).\n    66→\n    67→You still need to build the Docker image separately. Clone the repository and\n    68→run:\n    69→\n    70→```\n    71→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    72→cd cloche\n    73→make docker-build\n    74→```\n    75→\n    76→## Pre-built Release Binaries (Planned)\n    77→\n    78→> **Note:** Pre-built release binaries are not yet available. This section\n    79→> describes the planned installation method for when releases are published.\n    80→\n    81→Download pre-built binaries from the\n    82→[GitHub Releases](https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases) page. Each\n    83→release will include archives for common platforms (Linux amd64, Linux arm64,\n    84→macOS amd64, macOS arm64).\n    85→\n    86→```\n    87→# Example: Linux amd64\n    88→curl -LO https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases/latest/download/cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\n    89→tar xzf cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\n    90→sudo install cloche cloched cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/\n    91→```\n    92→\n    93→You still need to build the Docker image. Clone the repo and run\n    94→`make docker-build`:\n    95→\n    96→```\n    97→git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    98→cd cloche\n    99→make docker-build\n   100→```\n   101→\n   102→## Homebrew (macOS / Linux) (Planned)\n   103→\n   104→> **Note:** A Homebrew tap is not yet published. This section describes the\n   105→> planned installation method.\n   106→\n   107→```\n   108→brew tap cloche-dev/tap\n   109→brew install cloche\n   110→```\n   111→\n   112→This will install all three binaries. You will still need the Docker image —\n   113→the formula will print post-install instructions for building or pulling it.\n   114→\n   115→## Copy Binaries\n   116→\n   117→If you have already built Cloche on one machine, you can copy the three\n   118→binaries (`cloche`, `cloched`, `cloche-agent`) to another machine directly.\n   119→This is useful for air-gapped environments or quick ad-hoc deployments where\n   120→you do not want to install Go on the target.\n   121→\n   122→Build on the source machine (cross-compile if architectures differ):\n   123→\n   124→```\n   125→# Native build\n   126→make build\n   127→\n   128→# Cross-compile for Linux arm64\n   129→GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 go build -o bin/cloche-linux-arm64 ./cmd/cloche\n   130→GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 go build -o bin/cloched-linux-arm64 ./cmd/cloched\n   131→GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 go build -o bin/cloche-agent-linux-arm64 ./cmd/cloche-agent\n   132→```\n   133→\n   134→Copy and install on the target:\n   135→\n   136→```\n   137→scp bin/cloche bin/cloched bin/cloche-agent target-host:/tmp/\n   138→ssh target-host 'sudo install /tmp/cloche /tmp/cloched /tmp/cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/'\n   139→```\n   140→\n   141→You still need the Docker image on the target. Either build it there:\n   142→\n   143→```\n   144→ssh target-host 'git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git && cd cloche && make docker-build'\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→Or export/import the image:\n   148→\n   149→```\n   150→# On source machine\n   151→docker save cloche-agent:latest | gzip > cloche-agent.tar.gz\n   152→\n   153→# On target machine\n   154→docker load < cloche-agent.tar.gz\n   155→```\n   156→\n   157→## Docker-Only Usage (Planned)\n   158→\n   159→> **Note:** A dedicated `Dockerfile.daemon` for running the daemon in Docker\n   160→> does not exist yet. This section describes a planned future option.\n   161→\n   162→Running the Cloche daemon inside Docker would avoid any host installation\n   163→beyond Docker itself. This is useful for CI environments, ephemeral build\n   164→servers, or trying Cloche without installing Go.\n   165→\n   166→Once available, usage would look like:\n   167→\n   168→```\n   169→docker run -d \\\n   170→  --name cloched \\\n   171→  -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock \\\n   172→  -v /tmp/cloche.sock:/tmp/cloche.sock \\\n   173→  -e ANTHROPIC_API_KEY \\\n   174→  cloche-daemon\n   175→```\n   176→\n   177→Docker-in-Docker requires mounting the Docker socket. The CLI (`cloche`)\n   178→still needs to be available on the host (or in the same container) to\n   179→communicate with the daemon over the Unix socket.\n   180→\n   181→### CI Integration\n   182→\n   183→In a CI pipeline (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, etc.), the Docker-only approach\n   184→avoids installing Go on runners. Until the daemon image is published, you can\n   185→build it as a CI step:\n   186→\n   187→```yaml\n   188→# GitHub Actions example\n   189→- name: Build Cloche\n   190→  run: |\n   191→    git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git /tmp/cloche\n   192→    cd /tmp/cloche && make build && make docker-build\n   193→    sudo install /tmp/cloche/bin/* /usr/local/bin/\n   194→```\n   195→\n   196→## Verifying the Installation\n   197→\n   198→After installing, verify that everything works:\n   199→\n   200→```\n   201→# Check the binaries\n   202→cloche --help\n   203→cloched --help\n   204→\n   205→# Start the daemon (if not already running)\n   206→cloched &\n   207→\n   208→# Build the agent image\n   209→make docker-build\n   210→\n   211→# Run a quick test from any git repository with a .cloche/ directory\n   212→cloche list\n   213→```\n   214→\n   215→## Upgrading\n   216→\n   217→To upgrade an existing installation, repeat your original installation method.\n   218→If you built from source:\n   219→\n   220→```\n   221→cd cloche\n   222→git pull\n   223→make install\n   224→```\n   225→\n   226→The `make install` target stops the running daemon, installs the new binaries,\n   227→and restarts the daemon automatically.\n   228→\n   229→## Next Steps\n   230→\n   231→- [Usage guide](USAGE.md) — quick start, CLI reference, and workflow setup\n   232→- [Workflow DSL reference](workflows.md) — full syntax for `.cloche` files\n   233→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ea6e9045-ac0a-4147-be41-389c9a385d3e","uuid":"3b7f6008-a950-48f2-9576-ab42e8de107e","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/INSTALL.md","content":"# Installation\n\nThis document covers the various ways to install Cloche on your machine.\n\n## Prerequisites\n\nAll installation methods require:\n\n- **Docker** — Cloche runs workflows in containers\n- **Git** — result extraction uses git worktrees\n- **`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`** — for agent steps using Claude Code\n\n## Method Comparison\n\n| Method | Requires Go | Auto Docker Image | Best For |\n|--------|:-----------:|:-----------------:|----------|\n| [Build from source](#build-from-source) | Yes | Yes | Contributors, full control |\n| [`go install`](#go-install) | Yes | No | Go developers, quick setup |\n| [Pre-built binaries](#pre-built-release-binaries-planned) | No | No | Most users (planned) |\n| [Homebrew](#homebrew-macos--linux-planned) | No | No | macOS / Linux (planned) |\n| [Copy binaries](#copy-binaries) | No | No | Air-gapped or ad-hoc deploys |\n| [Docker-only](#docker-only-usage-planned) | No | N/A | CI, no host install (planned) |\n\nAll methods except Docker-only require building the `cloche-agent` Docker image\nseparately (unless the method does it automatically).\n\n## Build from Source\n\nClone the repository, build the binaries and Docker image, and install them:\n\n```\ngit clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\ncd cloche\nmake install\n```\n\n`make install` builds all three binaries (`cloche`, `cloched`, `cloche-agent`),\nbuilds the `cloche-agent:latest` Docker image, installs the binaries to\n`~/.local/bin/`, and starts the daemon. You can change the install prefix:\n\n```\nmake install PREFIX=/usr/local\n```\n\nMake sure the install prefix is on your `PATH`:\n\n```\nexport PATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\"\n```\n\n### Build Requirements\n\n- Go 1.25+\n\n## `go install`\n\nIf you have Go installed, you can install the binaries directly:\n\n```\ngo install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche@latest\ngo install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloched@latest\ngo install github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/cmd/cloche-agent@latest\n```\n\nThis places the binaries in `$GOPATH/bin` (or `$HOME/go/bin` by default).\n\nYou still need to build the Docker image separately. Clone the repository and\nrun:\n\n```\ngit clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\ncd cloche\nmake docker-build\n```\n\n## Pre-built Release Binaries (Planned)\n\n> **Note:** Pre-built release binaries are not yet available. This section\n> describes the planned installation method for when releases are published.\n\nDownload pre-built binaries from the\n[GitHub Releases](https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases) page. Each\nrelease will include archives for common platforms (Linux amd64, Linux arm64,\nmacOS amd64, macOS arm64).\n\n```\n# Example: Linux amd64\ncurl -LO https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche/releases/latest/download/cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\ntar xzf cloche-linux-amd64.tar.gz\nsudo install cloche cloched cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/\n```\n\nYou still need to build the Docker image. Clone the repo and run\n`make docker-build`:\n\n```\ngit clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\ncd cloche\nmake docker-build\n```\n\n## Homebrew (macOS / Linux) (Planned)\n\n> **Note:** A Homebrew tap is not yet published. This section describes the\n> planned installation method.\n\n```\nbrew tap cloche-dev/tap\nbrew install cloche\n```\n\nThis will install all three binaries. You will still need the Docker image —\nthe formula will print post-install instructions for building or pulling it.\n\n## Copy Binaries\n\nIf you have already built Cloche on one machine, you can copy the three\nbinaries (`cloche`, `cloched`, `cloche-agent`) to another machine directly.\nThis is useful for air-gapped environments or quick ad-hoc deployments where\nyou do not want to install Go on the target.\n\nBuild on the source machine (cross-compile if architectures differ):\n\n```\n# Native build\nmake build\n\n# Cross-compile for Linux arm64\nGOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 go build -o bin/cloche-linux-arm64 ./cmd/cloche\nGOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 go build -o bin/cloched-linux-arm64 ./cmd/cloched\nGOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 go build -o bin/cloche-agent-linux-arm64 ./cmd/cloche-agent\n```\n\nCopy and install on the target:\n\n```\nscp bin/cloche bin/cloched bin/cloche-agent target-host:/tmp/\nssh target-host 'sudo install /tmp/cloche /tmp/cloched /tmp/cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/'\n```\n\nYou still need the Docker image on the target. Either build it there:\n\n```\nssh target-host 'git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git && cd cloche && make docker-build'\n```\n\nOr export/import the image:\n\n```\n# On source machine\ndocker save cloche-agent:latest | gzip > cloche-agent.tar.gz\n\n# On target machine\ndocker load < cloche-agent.tar.gz\n```\n\n## Docker-Only Usage (Planned)\n\n> **Note:** A dedicated `Dockerfile.daemon` for running the daemon in Docker\n> does not exist yet. This section describes a planned future option.\n\nRunning the Cloche daemon inside Docker would avoid any host installation\nbeyond Docker itself. This is useful for CI environments, ephemeral build\nservers, or trying Cloche without installing Go.\n\nOnce available, usage would look like:\n\n```\ndocker run -d \\\n  --name cloched \\\n  -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock \\\n  -v /tmp/cloche.sock:/tmp/cloche.sock \\\n  -e ANTHROPIC_API_KEY \\\n  cloche-daemon\n```\n\nDocker-in-Docker requires mounting the Docker socket. The CLI (`cloche`)\nstill needs to be available on the host (or in the same container) to\ncommunicate with the daemon over the Unix socket.\n\n### CI Integration\n\nIn a CI pipeline (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, etc.), the Docker-only approach\navoids installing Go on runners. Until the daemon image is published, you can\nbuild it as a CI step:\n\n```yaml\n# GitHub Actions example\n- name: Build Cloche\n  run: |\n    git clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git /tmp/cloche\n    cd /tmp/cloche && make build && make docker-build\n    sudo install /tmp/cloche/bin/* /usr/local/bin/\n```\n\n## Verifying the Installation\n\nAfter installing, verify that everything works:\n\n```\n# Check the binaries\ncloche --help\ncloched --help\n\n# Start the daemon (if not already running)\ncloched &\n\n# Build the agent image\nmake docker-build\n\n# Run a quick test from any git repository with a .cloche/ directory\ncloche list\n```\n\n## Upgrading\n\nTo upgrade an existing installation, repeat your original installation method.\nIf you built from source:\n\n```\ncd cloche\ngit pull\nmake install\n```\n\nThe `make install` target stops the running daemon, installs the new binaries,\nand restarts the daemon automatically.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n- [Usage guide](USAGE.md) — quick start, CLI reference, and workflow setup\n- [Workflow DSL reference](workflows.md) — full syntax for `.cloche` files\n","numLines":233,"startLine":1,"totalLines":233}}}
